## Level 4 → Level 5
**Objective:** Find the only human readable file among 10 files in
the `inhere` directory, all named `-file00` to `-file09`.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
cd inhere              # moved into the inhere directory
ls -la                 # listed all files: -file00 through -file09
cat ./-file00          # checked files one by one
cat ./-file07          # found the human readable password here
```

**What I Learned:**
- Only one file contained human readable text — the rest contained
  binary/garbage data which is unreadable
- Used `./` prefix because all filenames started with `-` (hyphen)
- Checked files manually one by one this time — inefficient but works

**Smarter Way I Could Have Done It:**
The `file` command checks what type of data is inside a file
without opening it. Could have run:
```bash
file ./-file0*         # checks all files at once and labels each type
```
This would have instantly shown which file is "ASCII text" 
(human readable) vs "data" (binary) without opening each one.
Output would look like:
```
./-file00: data
./-file01: data
./-file02: data
./-file07: ASCII text    ← this is the one
./-file09: data
```

**Key Takeaway:**
Always use the `file` command when dealing with multiple unknown
files — in real pentesting you won't have time to open files one
by one. `file ./*` will instantly tell you what each file contains.
